<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - CYLINDER SLEEVE
        REMOVAL - CYLINDER SLEEVES
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="hl4150603" svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="6">
        <title>CYLINDER SLEEVES</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title></title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Effective with S/N 532981 production and all service cylinder sleeves have a one inch recess
                        below the sealing surface of the sleeve flange. This recess is used to allow additional coolant
                        to flow to the top ring belt area of the cylinder sleeve. Refer to Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150629">6.29</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect inside surface of sleeve for scuffing or scoring. Replace sleeve (and
                    piston) as required. Examine outer surface of sleeve for cavitation erosion, replace as required.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>While scalloped cylinder sleeves are hardened they do not have twin dot identification
                            marking on fire ring area as before.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check cylinder sleeves for wear (taper) using any one of the three methods described.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>
                <emph type="underscr">METHOD ONE</emph>
            </title>
            <para>"TELESCOPING GAUGE METHOD" (
                <emph type="bold">Figures
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150630">6.30</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150631">6.31</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ).
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a telescoping gauge and an outside micrometer:</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure sleeve I.D. at top of piston ring travel (just below carbon ridge area) and
                    record reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure sleeve. I.D. below ring travel area and record reading.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Difference between the two readings is the cylinder sleeve taper. If specifications are
                    exceeded, replace sleeve.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150628" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11567" filename="../figcg1/CG11567.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.28. Measure Piston Pin O.D. to Check for Wear.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150629" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12525" filename="../figcg1/CG12525.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.29. Cylinder Sleeve Comparison.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150630" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11866" filename="../figcg1/CG11866.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.30. Check Cylinder Sleeve I.D. @ Top of Ring Travel.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>
                <emph type="underscr">METHOD TWO</emph>
            </title>
            <para>"DIAL BORE GAUGE METHOD" (
                <emph type="bold">Figures
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150632">6.32</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150633">6.33</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ).
            </para>
            <para>Using a dial bore gauge:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure at the top of the piston ring travel just below the carbon ridge area and record
                    the reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure below the ring travel area and record the reading.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The difference between the two readings is the cylinder sleeve taper. If specifications
                    are exceeded, replace the sleeve.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150631" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12110" filename="../figcg1/CG12110.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.31. Check Cylinder Sleeve I.D. @ Below Ring Travel.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150632" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12111" filename="../figcg1/CG12111.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.32. Check Cylinder Sleeve I.D. @ Top of Ring Travel.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150633" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12112" filename="../figcg1/CG12112.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.33. Check Cylinder Sleeve I.D. @ Below Ring Travel Area.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>
                <emph type="underscr">METHOD THREE</emph>
            </title>
            <para>"FEELER GAUGE METHOD" (
                <emph type="bold">Figures
                    <hotlnk document="e415_115.xml" xrefid="ef4150634">6.34</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk document="e415_115.xml" xrefid="ef4150635">6.35</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ).
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a top compression ring squarely at the top of ring travel and measure the ring
                    end gap with a feeler gauge. Record the reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the same piston ring below the ring travel area and measure the ring end gap.
                    Record the readings.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Every 0.076 mm (0.003 in.) increase in ring gap equals a 0.025 mm (0.001 in.) increase
                    in bore size.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the sleeve is worn beyond specifications, replace the sleeve.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
